04312nam a22005055i 9780773566743DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735667437 a10.1515/97807735667432doi  a(DE-B1597)656929  a(OCoLC)732600872  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR99bS578 1997eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a8011 aSolway, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRandom Walks :bEssays in Elective Criticism /cDavid Solway. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tRandom Walks -- tPart One -- tNever on Sontag -- tCulling and Dereading, or the Pursuit of Absence -- tThe Autoerotic Text -- tOn the Essay, or the Jubilation of the Lambda -- tThe End of Poetry -- tThe Word and the Stone -- tFellatiotics: The Relation between Surface and Depth -- tNotes on Lucianic Satire -- tPart Two -- tThe Trial As Jewish Joke -- tFraming Layton -- tPronominal Debris -- tIntoxicated Words: Language in Shakespeare’s Late Romances -- tDukes and Duchesses: A Minority View of “My Last Duchess” -- tJoyces’s Choices -- tSwift and Sartorism -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first section of the book develops Solway's approach to literature, starting from the assumption that genuine criticism requires the intellectual freedom to range at will across the literary landscape rather than restricting one's direction based on what is current, fashionable, or politically correct. Solway argues that advocating a theoretical school - postmodernism, poststructuralism, semiotics, new historicism, Marxist revisionism, or queer theory - generally involves abandoning the real critical project, which is the discovery of one's own undetermined motives, dispositions, and interests as reflected in the secret mirrors embedded in literary texts. Instead Solway pursues what he calls elective criticism, writing that enables the critical writer to freely discover his or her own identity - a concept that he claims cannot reasonably be diluted, relinquished, or deconstructed. In the second section Solway practices what he preaches, exploring a wide range of authors and subjects. His essays include an analysis of Franz Kafka's The Trial as a Jewish joke, a personal memoir of Irving Layton, an interpretation of Erin Moure's "Pronouns on the Main," an examination of language in William Shakespeare's romances, a reading of Robert Browning's "My Last Duchess" that is sympathetic to the Duke, an assertion that James Joyce has more in common with the traditional novelist than with the professional, (post-)modern alienator, and an exploration of Jonathan Swift's sartorial imagery that contends that form is the source of substantive identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356674340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566743/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles